</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kevorkian had given the videotape to CBS, which later turned it
over to prosecutors. Mike Wallace, a reporter on the show, said the
tape was handed over because ``it belonged to Dr. Kevorkian,'' and
that is what he wished to be done.
</P>
<P>
   On the tape, Kevorkian is shown presenting a consent form to
Youk, who then signed it.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights later, on Sept. 17, Kevorkian is shown injecting Youk
with drugs to make him sleep, then stop breathing, and then stop
his heart.
</P>
<P>
   When asked during the broadcast if he had killed Youk, Kevorkian
replied, ``I did.''
</P>
